me from Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’. Compare   Fehn  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 馮, see   Feng   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Fehn","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a bog or marsh, from <i>fehn</i> ‘bog’.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of the three farms in southeastern Norway named Fen, probably from Old Norse <i>Fávin</i>, of which the second element is <i>vin</i> ‘meadow’; the first element is unexplained."]},{"name":"Fenner","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-er</i>, a topographic name for someone who lived in or by a marsh or fen. Fenn Place in Worth in Sussex had owners called <i>atte Fenne</i>, who in the time of King Henry VI (1421–1471) apparently changed their name to <i>Fenner</i>. See   Fenn  .","English: variant of <b>Fainer</b>, from Middle English <i>feiner</i>, <i>fener</i> ‘haymonger, one who sells hay’ (Old French <i>fenier</i>), or perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>feiner</i> ‘inventor; hypocrite’.","South German and Swiss German: occupational name for an ensign or standard bearer, from Middle High German <i>vener</i>, an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>vane</i> ‘flag’. See also   Fenrich  ."]},{"name":"Fenning","meanings":["English: topographic name from Middle English <i>fen(ne)</i> ‘fen, marsh’ (Old English <i>fenn</i>) + <i>-ing</i>, for someone who lived by a fen or marsh. Compare   Fenn  ."]},{"name":"Finner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt.","German: topographic name from an agent derivative of Old High German <i>fenni</i>, Middle Low German and Old Frisian <i>fenne</i> ‘bog’ (see   Fenn  ).","German: ethnic name for a Finn (see   Finn   4)."]}]},{"name":"Peter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Peter Fenn was born about 1330, in Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England. He had at least 1 son. He died in England, and was buried in Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England."},"et":{"about 1330–":"umbes 1330–Surnud","1355–1409":"1355–1409","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1337":"1337","1355":"1355","1453":"1453","1330":"1330","1382":"1382","1409":"1409","about 1330":"umbes 1330","England":"England","Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"about 1330–":"noin 1330–Kuollut","1355–1409":"1355–1409","13